                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-3" data-i18n="whatIsAc">What is Alternating Current?</h3>
                    <p class="theory-text" data-i18n="theoryP1">
                        <strong>Alternating Current (AC)</strong> is the flow of electric charge that periodically reverses direction. Unlike Direct Current (DC) which flows steadily in one direction (like from a battery), AC is the standard type of electricity delivered to businesses and residences worldwide.
                    </p>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-3" data-i18n="sineWaveTitle">The Sine Wave Characteristics</h3>
                    <p class="theory-text" data-i18n="theoryP2">
                        The most common AC waveform is a sine wave. It is created by a generator that rotates a coil in a magnetic field. As it rotates, the voltage smoothly rises to a peak, falls to zero, goes to a negative peak, and returns to zero.
                        <br><br>
                        In this simulation, we assume a <strong>purely resistive load</strong>. This means the voltage and current are perfectly in sync with each other (Phase Angle φ = 0). When voltage is at its peak, current is also at its peak.
                    </p>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Right Column: Formulas and Mathematical Foundations -->
